While the additional detail in option (b) about Tom wanting to continue using his new stereo without issues may seem reasonable, selecting (b) would be an example of the conjunction fallacy. The conjunction fallacy is when we erroneously judge a more detailed scenario as being more probable than a simpler one, even though in reality, adding more specifics makes the scenario less likely, not more likely.

Since (b) contains (a) plus additional details, (b) cannot be more probable than (a) alone. Tom paying the ticket is more probable than Tom paying the ticket AND having a specific motivation for doing so. Therefore, (a) is the better answer.
